04912nam a22008895i 9780231512572DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315125727 a10.7312/kuni142182doi  a(DE-B1597)459032  a(OCoLC)1013955218  a(OCoLC)1029824655  a(OCoLC)1032678394  a(OCoLC)1037970778  a(OCoLC)1042013331  a(OCoLC)1046612024  a(OCoLC)1047000397  a(OCoLC)1049680244  a(OCoLC)1054876188  a(OCoLC)979967634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aF805.J4bK86 2009 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a305.892407892221 aKunin, Seth, eauthor.10aJuggling Identities :bIdentity and Authenticity Among the Crypto-Jews /cSeth Kunin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Diversity and Complexity -- tTwo. The Case Against the Authenticity of Crypto- Judaism in New Mexico -- tThree. The Case for the Authenticity of Crypto- Judaism in New Mexico -- tFour. Ideal Types of Crypto- Jewish Identity -- tFive. Crypto- Jewish Practice -- tSix. A Postmodern Take on Crypto- Judaism -- tConclusion -- tTheoretical Appendix. (Neo)- Structuralism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuggling Identities is an extensive ethnography of the crypto-Jews who live deep within the Hispanic communities of the American Southwest. Critiquing scholars who challenge the cultural authenticity of these individuals, Seth D. Kunin builds a solid link between the crypto-Jews of New Mexico and their Spanish ancestors who secretly maintained their Jewish identity after converting to Catholicism, offering the strongest evidence yet of their ethnic and religious origins. Kunin adopts a unique approach to the lives of modern crypto-Jews, concentrating primarily on their understanding of Jewish tradition and the meaning they ascribe to ritual. He illuminates the complexity of this community, in which individuals and groups perform the same practice in diverse ways. Kunin supplements his ethnographic research with broader theories concerning the nature of identity and memory, which is especially applicable to crypto-Jews, whose culture resides mainly in memory. Kunin's work has wider implications, not only for other forms of crypto-Judaism (such as that found in the former Soviet Union) but also for the study of Judaism's fluid nature, which helps adherents adapt to new circumstances and knowledge. Kunin draws fascinating comparisons between the intricate ancestry of crypto-Jews and those of other ethnic communities living in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCrypto-JewszNew MexicoxHistory. 0aJewszNew MexicoxHistory. 0aJewszNew MexicoxIdentity. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kuni14218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231512572.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  